posts.cooked: So I know how to code in Java. But my team’s programmers rarely showed up to club times and my mentors didn’t teach anything about programming to me. Even though I tried to learn from the programmers in my team they didn’t bother to spend extra time teaching me and I also kind of dismissed it after they weren’t willing to teach me. The programmers that are 2 grades above me now graduated and I don’t want to let my team down so I want to learn programming for FRC . What should I do?

posts.name: Ira Pino
posts.cooked:
9496 LYNK’s site for housing knowledge and information for the team.

This site from 9496 has a whole bunch of different resources. I’m not a programmer so I don’t know how good these resources are but this is where I’d start.

posts.name: Curt Rozeboom
posts.cooked: Those are some great resources. My advice, start with anything from 3487 Spectrum, just to help you ‘eat the elephant’. I’d also ask, do you have access to a robot that you could spend time learning on, say from last year? Even just a drive-train will help. If not, could you get your team to buy you an XRP to practice with? There is also a lot you can do in simulation mode running on your own computer, but that does take a little bit of extra knowledge to get started with, however if you wanted to go this route I’d recommend starting with YAGSL ’s Example Code as much of it is built to be simulated and it’s a good place to learn swerve.

posts.cooked: there are some good youtube videos, i recommend finding somebody online to help you. what i did is i acted like i was coding a demo bot that is like just an arm or just a drivetrain, and then i would send it to somebody better to check. That helped me learn the code structure alot. try recoding the robot last year completely from scratch maybe, learning how to do things as you go like subsystems and commands.

posts.name: 4391 Programming Mentor
posts.cooked: IMO - It’s tough to learn.  And can be tough to teach.  But you’re asking well before the next season so you’re off to a great start!  I’d suggest making sure you have access to 2025’s robot code.  I’m sure you have familiarity with the 2025 robot’s capabilities.  Think about something the robot did (rotate an arm, extend an elevator, etc…) and then stare at the code and try and make sense of it.  You’ll end up with many more questions, but they’ll be more detailed in nature, and will be able to find the answer to those specific questions.  One by one, you’ll learn how your robot did what it did, and you’ll come across other examples of things in your searching (maybe better methods), and you’ll get it.  It will take a lot of patience.

we’ve put together some FRC -specific software training materials on 8033 here: GitHub - HighlanderRobotics/Highlanders-Training: Training materials for FRC 8033 . they’re currently undergoing some revisions for this year and do have some 8033 specific stuff, but hopefully you find this to be a useful starting point!

Mochatitan:

try recoding the robot last year completely from scratch

^^^ this is a great exercise to get an idea of the “shape” of robot code and is also a great place to look for places to improve. if you see code and don’t understand why it’s written like that or if you can think of a better way to write it, try rewriting it in a way that makes sense for you. the best way to learn is to just get started on a project and look up the things you need along the way. also, there’s lots of people online who are willing to help!

posts.cooked: Reading other teams codes improves your skill to write creative and effective code. There are bunch of github repo’s and blogs posted about it. Go read their code understand their code structure. How much you read a quality code you are going to think and write the code faster. Also another option is getting through some problems. If you have a lot of trouble try to learn it and if the problem happens again think about your learnings and solve it.
